04721nam a22005535i 9780822388654DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223886547 a10.1515/97808223886542doi  a(DE-B1597)553186  a(OCoLC)1170721922  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHD6072.2.C6bY36 2008 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a331.409512221 aYan, Hairong, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Masters, New Servants :bMigration, Development, and Women Workers in China /cHairong Yan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b2 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Emaciation of the Rural: "No Way Out" -- t2. Mind and Body, Gender and Class -- tPart I. "Intellectuals' Burdens" and Domestic Labor -- tPart II. Searching for the Proper Baomu -- tIntermezzo 1. A Survey of Employers -- t3. Suzhi as a New Human Value: Neoliberal Governance of Labor Migration -- tIntermezzo 2. Urban Folklore on Neoliberalism -- t4. A Mirage of Modernity: Pas de Deux of Consumption and Production -- t5. Self-Development and the Specter of Class -- tIntermezzo 3. Diary and Song -- t6. The Economic Law and Liminal Subjects -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn March 9, 1996, tens of thousands of readers of a daily newspaper in China's Anhui province saw a photograph of two young women at a local long-distance bus station. Dressed in fashionable new winter coats and carrying luggage printed with Latin letters, the women were returning home from their jobs in one of China's large cities. As the photo caption indicated, the image represented the "transformation of migrant women"; the women's "transformation" was signaled by their status as consumers. New Masters, New Servants is an ethnography of class dynamics and the subject formation of migrant domestic workers. Based on her interviews with young women who migrated from China's Anhui province to the city of Beijing to engage in domestic service for middle-class families, as well as interviews with employers, job placement agencies, and government officials, Yan Hairong explores what these migrant workers mean to the families that hire them, to urban economies, to rural provinces such as Anhui, and to the Chinese state. Above all, Yan focuses on the domestic workers' self-conceptions, desires, and struggles.Yan analyzes how the migrant women workers are subjected to, make sense of, and reflect on a range of state and neoliberal discourses about development, modernity, consumption, self-worth, quality, and individual and collective longing and struggle. She offers keen insight into the workers' desire and efforts to achieve suzhi (quality) through self-improvement, the way workers are treated by their employers, and representations of migrant domestic workers on television and the Internet and in newspapers and magazines. In so doing, Yan demonstrates that contestations over the meanings of migrant workers raise broad questions about the nature of wage labor, market economy, sociality, and postsocialism in contemporary China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aRural womenxEmploymentzChina. 0aRural-urban migrationzChina. 0aWomen household employeeszChinaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388654zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt